    <div class="crop_activity_info">
      <h3>How our crop recommendations work</h3>
      <p>The crop recommendations in this app follow the principle of crop rotation. Crop rotation involves growing different crops on arable land to keep the nutrient content in the soil balanced. Most crop families require the same the nutrients from soil, however they all drain the nutrients at different quantites. So if one crop family was to be repeatly used on arable land, the family's most required nutrients in the soil will be depeleted quickly, however other nutrients in the soil which the family does not require, will not be put to use. Crop rotation also reduces the build-up of crop-specific pest and disease problems.</p>
      <br/>
      <p><b>Crop families recommendation order:</b></p>


      <p>Liliaceae/Allium</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Asparagus and onions.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and potassium.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Brassicaceae/Brassicas/Crucifiers</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Broccoli, cabbage and turnip.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Calcium and nitrogen.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Cucurbitaceae/Cucurbits</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Cucumbers, pumpkins, squash and melon.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Phosphorus and potassium.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Chenopodiaceae/Chenopods</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Beetroot and spinach.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and potassium.</li>
      </ul>

      
      <p>Ericaceae</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Blueberries.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Low quantities of nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Asteraceae/Chicories</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Lettuce.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and potassium.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Fabaceae/Legumes*</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Beans, lentils, and peas.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Balanced and low quantities amoungst general crop nutrients.</li>
          <li>* These crops have relationships with bacteria that involves the formation of nitrogen that can be absorbed into soil.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Poaceae/Gramineae</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Corn, rice, sugarcane, and wheat.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and phosphate.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Rosaceae/Rose family</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Apple trees, blackberries, cherry trees, pear trees and strawberries.</li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Calcium, nitrogen and potassium.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Solanaceae/Nightshades</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Peppers, potatoes, and tomatoes. </li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and phosphorus.</li>
      </ul>


      <p>Apiaceae/Umbellifera/Umbels</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Crops - Carrots and parsnips. </li>
          <li>Most required nutrient(s): Calcium and potassium.</li>
      </ul>
